/li> <li><a title="Network Management Research Group" href="nmrg">NMRG</a></li> <li><a title="Routing Research Group" href="rrg">RRG</a></li> <li><a title="Scalable Adaptive Multicast Research Group" href="samrg">SAMRG</a></li> <li><a title="Software-Defined Networking Research Group" href="sdnrg">SDNRG</a></li> </ul> <h2>Other Activities</h2> <ul> <li> <a href='anrp'>Applied Networking Research Prize</a> </li> </ul> <h2>Internet Research Steering Group</h2> <ul> <li> <a href='chair'>IRTF Chair</a> </li> </ul> <ul> <li> <a href='irsg'>IRSG Members</a> </li> </ul> <h2>IPR</h2> <ul> <li> <a href='ipr'>Intellectual Property Rights</a> </li> </ul> <h2>Sponsors</h2> <ul> <li> <a href='http://ietf.org/'> <img alt='Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF)' height='53' src='img/ietf.png' width='100'> </a> </li> <li> <a href='http://isoc.org/'> <img alt='Internet Society (ISOC)' height='40' src='img/isoc.png' width='100'> </a> </li> </ul> </div> <div class='main'> <a id='content'></a> <div class='rightbar'> <h2>Chairs</h2> <p> The NCRG is chaired by <a href="http://linkedin.com/in/mbehringer">Michael Behringer</a> (<a href="mailto:mbehring@cisco.com">mbehring@cisco.com</a>) and <a href="http://www.1-4-5.net/~dmm/vita.html">David Meyer</a> (<a href="mailto:dmm@1-4-5.net">dmm@1-4-5.net</a>). </p> <h2>Mailing List</h2> <p> The NCRG mailing list is <a href="mailto:ncrg@irtf.org">ncrg@irtf.org</a>. To subscribe or access the list archives, visit the <a href="/mailman/listinfo/ncrg">mailman page</a>. </p> <h2>Web Page</h2> <p> Additional NCRG information is available at <a href="http://networkcomplexity.org/">http://networkcomplexity.org/</a>. </p> <h2>Timeline</h2> <p>The NCRG was chartered on 2011-10-4.</p> </div> <h2>Charter</h2> <p> The <span class='term'>Network Complexity Research Group</span> (<a href="/ncrg">NCRG</a>) aims at defining and analyzing the complexity of IP-based networks. </p> <p>Complexity has been researched from a number of different angles, for example software complexity, or graph complexity. There is however no good, objective understanding of the complexity of a real IP network, including its operational aspects. When two competing approaches (e.g., protocols, network architectures) are discussed there is generally no measurable metric for complexity.</p> <p>There is a general perception that unnecessary complexity should be avoided, and when deciding between two approaches in networking, complexity is usual an important factor. However, the term &#8220;complexity&#8221; is rarely well defined, and decisions on complexity are mostly made on subjective terms.</p> <p>It would be highly desirable to have such metrics for network complexity to objectively compare IP networking approaches. The goal of this research group is to gain a better understanding of the underlying metrics of network complexity.</p> <p>The <a href="/ncrg">NCRG</a> provides objective definitions, metrics and background research to help making decisions where complexity is a factor. The ultimate goal is to provide factual and objective information and metrics to be used in network design and protocol design. It is highly desirable to have practical and objective information on network complexity as an input into the <a href="http://ietf.org/">IETF</a> process.</p> <p>Areas of interest include:</p> <ol> <li>Research with the goal of defining &#8220;network complexity&#8221;, and defining relevant metrics.</li> <li>Research on how to differentiate complexity between various network architectures, protocols or approaches.</li> <li>Methods and ideas to contain, control, or reduce complexity in IP based networks.</li> <li>Collect use cases regarding specific network designs or failure cases where complexity played a role.</li> </ol> <p> The group will report progress through <a href='http://networkcomplexity.org/'>http://networkcomplexity.org/</a> and presentations at <a href="http://ietf.org/">IETF</a> and <a href="./">IRTF</a> meetings. Relevant information and research developed by the research group will be submitted for publication as Experimental or Informational RFCs. </p> <h2>Membership</h2> Membership is open. <h2>Meetings</h2> <a href="/ncrg">NCRG</a> meetings are held at least once a year in conjunction with the <a href="http://ietf.org/">IETF</a>. Another yearly meeting should be held, e.g., in conjunction with an academic conference. </div> </div> <div class='layout_footer'></div> </div> <div class='footer noprint'> <div class='left'> <div class='socialshareprivacy'></div> </div> <div class='right'> <span id='ipv6'></span> <span> <a href='http://validator.w3.org/check/referer'>HTML</a> </span> <span> <a href='http://jigsaw.w3.org/css-validator/check/referer'>CSS</a> </span> <span> Modified: <time datetime='2011-09-26'>2011-09-26</time> </span> </div> </div> <script src='//ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/1.7.1/jquery.min.js'></script> <script>window.jQuery||document.write('<script src="jquery-1.7.1.min.js"><\/script>');$.getJSON("ipv6.json",function(b){if(b.ipv6){$("#ipv6").append("Thank you for using IPv6.")}});</script> <script src='socialshareprivacy.js'></script> <script>jQuery(document).ready(function(b){if(b(".socialshareprivacy").length>0){b(".socialshareprivacy").socialSharePrivacy({services:{facebook:{app_id:"194983820572921",dummy_img:"socialshareprivacy/images/dummy_facebook_en.png",txt_info:"Two clicks for more online privacy: Click here to enable the Facebook button. Enabling the button alone already transmits personal information to third parties.",txt_fb_off:"Facebook link active",txt_fb_on:"Facebook link inactive",language:"en_US",action:"recommend"},twitter:{dummy_img:"socialshareprivacy/images/dummy_twitter.png",txt_info:"Two clicks for more online privacy: Click here to enable the Twitter button. Enabling the button alone already transmits personal information to third parties.",txt_fb_off:"Twitter link active",txt_fb_on:"Twitter link inactive",language:"en"},gplus:{dummy_img:"so